Last week, I observed the emerging government condition of spectacular ineffectiveness in the face of monstrously engorged ministerial clout.
I argued that the burgeoning VIP culture signifies the consolidation of a baronial class, who no longer view themselves as the president’s subordinates, exercising borrowed executive power on his behalf, to serve the people of Kenya.



