Instead, they see themselves as active contenders vying with the political class for the opportunity to lord it over Kenyans and gratify their base physiological imperatives.
This is the only inference the reasonable mind may arrive at, after examining our public affairs, however briefly. Kenyans are not feeling served, respected or even seen by their government, despite the deployment of incredibly powerful ministerial power and expenditure of stupendous amounts of public funds.



