Stated in 2015, this intention would have had the effect of enhancing transparency and exposing the cartels who continue to devour the state.
Public procurement systems are not mundane bureaucratic quibbles. Nearly all public expenditure has an element of procurement. Over 50 per cent of the public budget goes to procurement. Procurement is the node where public budgets as public policy instruments find expression in terms of actual provision of citizen services.
A corrupted public procurement system perverts this node, so that procurement becomes the expression of the private interests of bandits.
As early as 2014, corruption was estimated to cost the country Sh635 billion. When the Head of Public Service made this revelation all those years ago, a good number of Kenyans thought he had exaggerated it a bit. Not anymore. Given the stampeding ruthlessness of present corruption, there is actually good reason to believe that the level is much higher.
All budgetary expenditures are made through MDAs — ministries, departments and agencies — which are presided over by Cabinet secretaries.
All public procurement, through which cartels siphon billions of shillings, take place right under the purview of Cabinet secretaries.



