Granted, they are formally not allowed to interfere in procurement matters. Yet, their policy and strategic leadership must surely be counted upon to create and maintain corruption-free programmes and projects. Moreover, non-participation in procurement affairs does not in any way impair their corruption prevention mandate.
In any event, a lot of MDA corruption invariably bear the telltale fingerprints of presiding officers. Every instance displays the unmistakable “handwriting” of ministerial complicity, collusion or arms-length participation.
The President has been a lone, despairing voice in the war on corruption. The silence of virtually the entire Cabinet, outside the disembodied and reluctant rote of prepared remarks, is truly startling.
Sh635 billion
The cumulative anti-corruption energy of sub-presidential Cabinet is an uninspiring and abject whimper, a neglected, dwindling flicker. If the President promotes the formal and de jure anti-corruption policy in word, his Cabinet project an informal, de facto corruption policy. I do not think it is wise to open bets on who is winning. Suffice it to say it is not a good look.
It would be lovely to be utterly mistaken on this matter, and I would relish the occasion to take back my words.



